      "code": "{\"filePath\": \"C:\\\\Users\\\\LLM-Test\\\\Documents\\\\agentsong\\\\issues\\\\issue-healthcare-data-interoperability.md\"}",
      "output": "<path>C:\\Users\\LLM-Test\\Documents\\agentsong\\issues\\issue-healthcare-data-interoperability.md</path>\n<type>file</type>\n<content>\n1: # Issue: Healthcare data interoperability — FreeStyle Libre context\n2: \n3: ## The problem\n4: \n5: Glucose data from FreeStyle Libre 2 is generated on-device, routed through Abbott's LibreView cloud, and export is manual, rate-limited, and UI-bound. Third-party interoperability is intentionally constrained.\n6: \n7: ## Legal context (what GDPR actually says)\n8: \n9: ### GDPR Article 20 — Right to data portability\n10: \n11: > \"The data subject shall have the right to receive the personal data concerning him or her, which he or she has provided to a controller, in a structured, commonly used and machine-readable format\"\n12: > — [EUR-Lex, Regulation (EU) 2016/679](https://eur-lex.europa.eu/legal-content/EN/TXT/?uri=CELEX%3A32016R0679)\n13: \n14: ### What GDPR requires vs. doesn't require\n15: \n16: | Requirement | Mandated? | Source |\n17: |---|---|---|\n18: | Export in structured, machine-readable format (CSV, JSON, XML) | **Yes** | Art. 20(1) |\n19: | Direct controller-to-controller transmission | **Conditional** — \"where technically feasible\" | Art. 20(2) |\n20: | APIs specifically | **No** — APIs are one implementation method, not a requirement | ICO guidance |\n21: | Interoperable formats | **Encouraged**, not required | Recital 68 |\n22: \n23: ### ICO guidance\n24: \n25: > \"Machine-readable data can be made directly available to applications that request that data over the web. This is undertaken by means of an application programming interface ('API'). **If you are able** to implement such a system then you can facilitate data exchanges.\"\n26: > — [ICO, Right to data portability](https://ico.org.uk/for-organisations/uk-gdpr-guidance-and-resources/individual-rights/individual-rights/right-to-data-portability)\n27: \n28: The ICO uses the conditional \"if you are able\" — APIs are presented as a helpful option, not a mandate.\n29: \n30: ### GDPR compliance baseline\n31: \n32: CSV export usually already satisfies compliance baseline. Even if it is annoying, manual, or behind a login.\n33: \n34: ## The stronger angle: healthcare interoperability\n35: \n36: ### FDA position on interoperability\n37: \n38: > \"Interoperable devices with the ability to share information across systems and platforms can: Improve patient care, Reduce errors and adverse events, Encourage innovation, and Enable more diverse study datasets.\"\n39: > — [FDA, Medical Device Interoperability](https://www.fda.gov/medical-devices/digital-health-center-excellence/medical-device-interoperability)\n40: \n41: ### Clinical decision latency\n42: \n43: > \"Every hour that passes before sepsis is diagnosed and treated, the risk of mortality increases by 7.6%. Real-time and contextual information is critical here.\"\n44: > — [Innovaccer](https://innovaccer.com/blogs/data-fidelity-and-latency-all-things-clinical)\n45: \n46: > \"When latency becomes chronic, clinicians compensate with inefficient workarounds that can degrade patient safety. Clinical systems latency is no longer an IT nuisance — it's a patient safety issue.\"\n47: > — [Silk](https://silk.us/blog/when-data-performance-becomes-a-patient-care-issue/)\n48: \n49: ### NHS FHIR mandate\n50: \n51: > \"Lack of access to an up-to-date medical history can affect the way patients are treated. The impact on treatment, particularly in an emergency situation, can be significant.\"\n52: > — [NHS England](https://www.england.nhs.uk/long-read/interoperability)\n53: \n54: > \"The NHS uses FHIR to make integration with APIs and services easier. FHIR is the global industry standard for passing healthcare data between systems.\"\n55: > — [NHS England](https://www.england.nhs.uk/long-read/interoperability)\n56: \n57: ### CMS Interop Rule (US)\n58: \n59: > \"ONC-certified health IT must expose a FHIR R4 Patient Access API giving patients access to all their EHI at no cost. Organizations that interfere with EHI access face civil monetary penalties up to $1 million per violation.\"\n60: > — [ONC Cures Act Final Rule](https://www.healthit.gov/information-blocking/)\n61: \n62: ### Information blocking is illegal (US)\n63: \n64: > \"The information blocking provisions require that patients and their physicians be given immediate electronic access to significant portions of the patient's EHI upon request, unless an exception applies.\"\n65: > — [Texas Medical Association](https://www.texmed.org/21stCCA)\n66: \n67: ### Real-world litigation\n68: \n69: > \"Health Gorilla filed a motion to dismiss a lawsuit brought earlier this year by Epic and several health systems alleging improper access to patient records. The motion called Epic's lawsuit 'an attack on interoperability.'\"\n70: > — [MedCity News, March 2026](https://medcitynews.com/2026/03/health-gorilla-epic-data-interoperability/)\n71: \n72: ### Clinical outcomes from interoperability\n73: \n74: > \"Intermountain Health medical informaticists have developed a novel and interoperable technology platform... In the studies, we demonstrated a 36% relative decrease in 30-day mortality for pneumonia patients, which is more than 100 lives saved annually.\"\n75: > — [Intermountain Health](https://news.intermountainhealth.org/intermountain-health-develops-real-time-interoperable-technology-platform-which-integrates-artificial-intelligence-into-clinical-workflows-to-help-clinicians-better-diagnose-and-treat-patients)\n76: \n77: ## What Abbott doesn't have (and why)\n78: \n79: It's not just negligence. It's usually:\n80: - Regulatory liability risk (medical device data misuse)\n81: - Clinical interpretation control (they don't want 3rd-party misreads)\n82: - Cybersecurity surface reduction\n83: - Commercial lock-in (yes, also this)\n84: \n85: The absence of APIs is not automatically a compliance failure — it's a design trade-off under regulated constraints.\n86: \n87: ## Realistic outcomes\n88: \n89: | Outcome | Likelihood |\n90: |---|---|\n91: | Full API mandate | Very unlikely |\n92: | Improved export UX | Possible |\n93: | Clarification of portability rights | Possible |\n94: | ICO dismissal (\"compliant enough\") | Likely baseline |\n95: | Informal pressure / best practice guidance | Plausible |\n96: \n97: ## AgentSON's role\n98: \n99: AgentSON is not a law enforcement tool. It's an interoperability representation layer. The gap it addresses:\n100: \n101: > **Health data portability is legally recognized but architecturally not standardized.**\n102: \n103: Law says \"you own your data.\" Systems still behave like \"data is leased via interface.\" That tension is why formats like AgentSON matter — not as GDPR enforcement, but as interoperability representations of system behaviour over time.\n104: \n105: ## Sources\n106: \n107: 1. GDPR Article 20: https://eur-lex.europa.eu/legal-content/EN/TXT/?uri=CELEX%3A32016R0679\n108: 2. ICO guidance: https://ico.org.uk/for-organisations/uk-gdpr-guidance-and-resources/individual-rights/individual-rights/right-to-data-portability\n109: 3. FDA interoperability: https://www.fda.gov/medical-devices/digital-health-center-excellence/medical-device-interoperability\n110: 4. NHS FHIR: https://www.england.nhs.uk/long-read/interoperability\n111: 5. ONC Cures Act: https://www.healthit.gov/information-blocking/\n112: 6. CMS-0057-F: https://www.cms.gov/newsroom/fact-sheets/cms-interoperability-prior-authorization-final-rule-cms-0057-f\n113: 7. Intermountain Health outcomes: https://news.intermountainhealth.org/\n114: 8. Epic litigation: https://medcitynews.com/2026/03/health-gorilla-epic-data-interoperability/\n\n(End of file - total 114 lines)\n</content>",
