    },
    {
      "type": "action",
      "tool": "read",
      "code": "{\"filePath\": \"C:\\\\Users\\\\LLM-Test\\\\Documents\\\\agentsong\\\\issues\\\\issue-competitive-landscape-agentlog.md\"}",
      "output": "<path>C:\\Users\\LLM-Test\\Documents\\agentsong\\issues\\issue-competitive-landscape-agentlog.md</path>\n<type>file</type>\n<content>\n1: # Issue: Competitive landscape — AgentLog (braintied/agentlog)\n2: \n3: ## Status\n4: \n5: **Pre-standard phase.** Multiple groups independently converge on portable agent execution representation. No standard formation, no lock-in effects, no dominant distribution channel yet.\n6: \n7: ## What exists (verified facts only)\n8: \n9: | | AgentSON | AgentLog |\n10: |---|---|---|\n11: | **GitHub stars** | — | 0 |\n12: | **Commits** | — | 9 |\n13: | **Working readers** | 9 | 2 (Claude Code, Watchtower) |\n14: | **Fine-tuning export** | Yes (Unsloth/Olive) | No |\n15: | **Healthcare data** | Yes (FreeStyle Libre) | No |\n16: | **License** | Apache 2.0 | Apache 2.0 |\n17: | **Language** | Python | TypeScript |\n18: | **Paid product** | No | Ora Cloud (claimed, unverified) |\n19: \n20: ## What we don't know\n21: \n22: - Team size at Braintied\n23: - Funding status\n24: - Actual adoption (both repos have 0 stars)\n25: - Whether Ora Cloud has paying customers\n26: \n27: ## The useful distinction\n28: \n29: | Axis | Enterprise-first | Developer-first |\n30: |------|-----------------|----------------|\n31: | Sales motion | consulting / contracts | OSS adoption |\n32: | Adoption path | CTO → org rollout | dev → grassroots |\n33: | Constraints | compliance, SOC2, audit | usability, flexibility |\n34: \n35: These are different go-to-market paths, not a competition yet.\n36: \n37: ## AgentSON's factual advantages\n38: \n39: 1. **9 readers vs 2** — covers Cursor, Cline, Aider (they don't)\n40: 2. **Fine-tuning export** — nobody else has Unsloth/Olive integration\n41: 3. **FreeStyle Libre 2** — no one else covers health data\n42: 4. **SOP library** — 14 operational procedures\n43: \n44: ## AgentLog's factual advantages\n45: \n46: 1. **TypeScript ecosystem** — where Cursor/Cline/Aider users live\n47: 2. **OTel GenAI mapping** — observability integration\n48: 3. **\"Cortex\" blog** — content marketing exists\n49: \n50: ## What actually matters\n51: \n52: Not \"who has more readers\" but \"what abstraction becomes the default mental model for agent execution representation.\"\n53: \n54: That depends on:\n55: - simplicity of the schema\n56: - integration with existing tools (LangChain, MCP, etc.)\n57: - clean separation of execution, memory, observability, training data\n58: - incremental adoptability\n59: \n60: ## Sources\n61: \n62: - AgentLog repo: https://github.com/braintied/agentlog\n63: - Watchtower repo: https://github.com/braintied/watchtower\n64: - Both have 0 stars as of July 2026\n\n(End of file - total 64 lines)\n</content>",
      "status": "success",
      "timestamp": 1783296348105
    },
    {
      "type": "action",
      "tool": "read",
      "code": "{\"filePath\": \"C:\\\\Users\\\\LLM-Test\\\\Documents\\\\agentsong\\\\issues\\\\issue-design-principle-intrinsic-before-extrinsic.md\"}",
      "output": "<path>C:\\Users\\LLM-Test\\Documents\\agentsong\\issues\\issue-design-principle-intrinsic-before-extrinsic.md</path>\n<type>file</type>\n<content>\n1: # Issue: Add \"Intrinsic Before Extrinsic\" design principle\n2: \n3: ## Summary\n4: \n5: Codify a design principle that prevents the AgentSON core specification from accumulating application-specific concerns. The four intrinsic properties of an AgentSON episode are:\n6: \n7: 1. **Fidelity** — does it accurately represent what happened?\n8: 2. **Portability** — can it move between systems?\n9: 3. **Replayability** — can the execution be reconstructed?\n10: 4. **Analyzability** — can humans and software inspect it?\n11: \n12: Everything else (fine-tuning, analytics, compliance, dashboards, archives, search, benchmarking) is an **extrinsic use** of the artifact, not a property of it.\n13: \n14: ## Proposed addition\n15: \n16: Add to `docs/standards/` (or a new `DESIGN-PRINCIPLES.md`):\n17: \n18: ```\n19: Design Principle — Intrinsic Before Extrinsic\n20: \n21: AgentSON Core SHALL evolve only to improve the intrinsic properties of an execution episode:\n22: \n23:   fidelity,\n24:   portability,\n25:   replayability,\n26:   analyzability.\n27: \n28: Applications that consume AgentSON (training, archives, dashboards, analytics,\n29: compliance, benchmarking, etc.) are intentionally outside the core specification.\n30: Their ability to exist is a consequence of the specification, not its purpose.\n31: ```\n32: \n33: ## Why this matters\n34: \n35: This gives a clear test for new feature proposals:\n36: \n37: > \"Does this change improve one of the four intrinsic properties?\"\n38: \n39: - If yes → candidate for core\n40: - If no → belongs in a downstream package, plugin, or application\n41: \n42: ## Analogies\n43: \n44: | Standard | What it doesn't know about |\n45: |----------|--------------------------|\n46: | Git | Pull requests |\n47: | PDF | E-signatures |\n48: | OpenTelemetry | Dashboards |\n49: | PCAP | Intrusion detection |\n50: | **AgentSON** | Fine-tuning, analytics, compliance |\n51: \n52: ## Suggested ADR\n53: \n54: ADR-012: Intrinsic Before Extrinsic — a constitutional rule for the AgentSON specification.\n55: \n56: ## Related\n57: \n58: - ADR-001: Why AgentSON Exists\n59: - ADR-004: Amber Design Tokens\n60: - ADR-010: GDPR/EU AI Act Data Liberation\n61: - ADR-011: Naming Change (agenson → AgentSON)\n\n(End of file - total 61 lines)\n</content>",
      "status": "success",
      "timestamp": 1783296348357
    },
    {
      "type": "action",
      "tool": "read",
      "code": "{\"filePath\": \"C:\\\\Users\\\\LLM-Test\\\\Documents\\\\agentsong\\\\issues\\\\issue-new-readers.md\"}",
      "output": "<path>C:\\Users\\LLM-Test\\Documents\\agentsong\\issues\\issue-new-readers.md</path>\n<type>file</type>\n<content>\n1: # Issue: Add Cursor, Cline, and Aider readers\n2: \n3: ## Summary\n4: \n5: Ship readers for Cursor, Cline, and Aider — covering Tier 1 and Tier 2 of the RICE roadmap. This brings AgentSON from 6 readers to 9, ahead of AgentLog (2 working readers).\n6: \n7: ## Readers added\n8: \n9: | Reader | Storage format | Tests | Status |\n10: |--------|---------------|-------|--------|\n11: | cursor | SQLite key-value (`state.vscdb`) | 10 | Working |\n12: | cline | JSON files (`api_conversation_history.json`) | 9 | Working |\n13: | aider | Markdown (`.aider.chat.history.md`) | 10 | Working |\n14: \n15: ## Files changed\n16: \n17: - `readers/cursor.py` — Cursor IDE reader\n18: - `readers/cline.py` — Cline VS Code extension reader\n19: - `readers/aider.py` — Aider CLI reader\n20: - `tests/test_cursor.py` — Cursor tests\n21: - `tests/test_cline.py` — Cline tests\n22: - `tests/test_aider.py` — Aider tests\n23: - `readers/__init__.py` — Updated exports\n24: - `cli/main.py` — Updated CLI to support cursor/cline/aider\n25: \n26: ## CLI usage\n27: \n28: ```bash\n29: agentson export --tool cursor --all --output ./sessions/\n30: agentson export --tool cline --all --output ./sessions/\n31: agentson export --tool aider --all --output ./sessions/\n32: agentson list --tool cursor\n33: agentson list --tool cline\n34: agentson list --tool aider\n35: ```\n36: \n37: ## Context\n38: \n39: AgentLog (braintied/agentlog) has Cursor, Cline, and Aider as \"planned\" but no working implementations. This PR puts AgentSON ahead with 9 working readers vs. AgentLog's 2.\n40: \n41: ## Test results\n42: \n43: 50/51 tests pass (1 pre-existing failure in `test_claude_code.py` unrelated to this change).\n44: \n45: ## PR\n46: \n47: Branch: `feat/cursor-cline-aider-readers`\n48: Commit: `25b843a`\n\n(End of file - total 48 lines)\n</content>",
      "status": "success",
      "timestamp": 1783296348626
    },
    {
      "type": "action",
      "tool": "read",
      "code": "{\"filePath\": \"C:\\\\Users\\\\LLM-Test\\\\Documents\\\\agentsong\\\\SOPs\\\\SOP-013-NHS-FHIR-Integration.md\"}",
      "output": "<path>C:\\Users\\LLM-Test\\Documents\\agentsong\\SOPs\\SOP-013-NHS-FHIR-Integration.md</path>\n<type>file</type>\n<content>\n1: # SOP-013: NHS FHIR Integration\n2: \n3: **Version:** 1.0  \n4: **Date:** 05 July 2026  \n5: **Author:** Andrea Enning (AndieKobbieTech)\n6: \n7: ---\n8: \n9: ## Purpose\n10: \n11: This SOP describes how to connect to NHS FHIR APIs for sharing glucose data with clinical systems.\n12: \n13: ---\n14: \n15: ## Prerequisites\n16: \n17: | Item | Requirement |\n18: |------|-------------|\n19: | **Data** | Glucose data in AgentSON format |\n20: | **Registration** | NHS Innovation Service (free) |\n21: | **Approval** | May need ICB partnership |\n22: \n23: ---\n24: \n25: ## Current NHS FHIR Status\n26: \n27: | Status | Detail |\n28: |--------|--------|\n29: | **Standard** | Under development (NHS 10-Year Plan) |\n30: | **Patient-initiated** | Aligned with our project |\n31: | **Access** | Requires NHS partnership or innovation registration |\n32: | **Timeline** | 12-24 months to full availability |\n33: \n34: ---\n35: \n36: ## Procedure\n37: \n38: ### Step 1: Register with NHS Innovation Service\n39: \n40: 1. Go to https://www.nhsinnovationservice.nhs.uk\n41: 2. Register as innovator (free)\n42: 3. Submit project details\n43: 4. Wait for approval\n44: \n45: ### Step 2: Understand FHIR Resources\n46: \n47: | Resource | What It Contains |\n48: |----------|------------------|\n49: | **Patient** | Patient demographics |\n50: | **Observation** | Glucose readings |\n51: | **Condition** | Diabetes diagnosis |\n52: | **MedicationStatement** | Current medications |\n53: | **DiagnosticReport** | Clinical reports |\n54: \n55: ### Step 3: Build FHIR Client (When Available)\n56: \n57: ```python\n58: import requests\n59: \n60: # FHIR base URL (when available)\n61: FHIR_BASE = \"https://fhir.nhs.uk/R4\"\n62: \n63: # Create Observation resource\n64: observation = {\n65:     \"resourceType\": \"Observation\",\n66:     \"status\": \"final\",\n67:     \"category\": [{\n68:         \"coding\": [{\n69:             \"system\": \"http://terminology.hl7.org/CodeSystem/observation-category\",\n70:             \"code\": \"laboratory\"\n71:         }]\n72:     }],\n73:     \"code\": {\n74:         \"coding\": [{\n75:             \"system\": \"http://loinc.org\",\n76:             \"code\": \"2345-7\",\n77:             \"display\": \"Glucose [Mass/volume] in Serum or Plasma\"\n78:         }]\n79:     },\n80:     \"subject\": {\"reference\": \"Patient/mother-id\"},\n81:     \"valueQuantity\": {\n82:         \"value\": 9.33,\n83:         \"unit\": \"mmol/L\"\n84:     },\n85:     \"effectiveDateTime\": \"2026-07-05T12:00:00Z\"\n86: }\n87: \n88: # POST to FHIR server (when available)\n89: # response = requests.post(f\"{FHIR_BASE}/Observation\", json=observation)\n90: ```\n91: \n92: ### Step 4: Export FHIR Bundle\n93: \n94: ```python\n95: def export_to_fhir(agentson_data):\n96:     \"\"\"Convert AgentSON glucose data to FHIR Bundle.\"\"\"\n97:     bundle = {\n98:         \"resourceType\": \"Bundle\",\n99:         \"type\": \"collection\",\n100:         \"entry\": []\n101:     }\n102:     \n103:     for entry in agentson_data[\"entries\"]:\n104:         if entry[\"type\"] == \"glucose_reading\":\n105:             fhir_obs = {\n106:                 \"resourceType\": \"Observation\",\n107:                 \"status\": \"final\",\n108:                 \"code\": {\n109:                     \"coding\": [{\n110:                         \"system\": \"http://loinc.org\",\n111:                         \"code\": \"2345-7\",\n112:                         \"display\": \"Glucose\"\n113:                     }]\n114:                 },\n115:                 \"valueQuantity\": {\n116:                     \"value\": entry[\"data\"][\"value\"],\n117:                     \"unit\": \"mmol/L\"\n118:                 },\n119:                 \"effectiveDateTime\": entry[\"timestamp\"]\n120:             }\n121:             bundle[\"entry\"].append({\"resource\": fhir_obs})\n122:     \n123:     return bundle\n124: ```\n125: \n126: ---\n127: \n128: ## What We Can Share Now\n129: \n130: | Data | Format | How |\n131: |------|--------|-----|\n132: | **Glucose readings** | PDF/HTML | Email to GP |\n133: | **Trends** | Chart image | Print for appointment |\n134: | **AgentSON files** | JSON | Share with developers |\n135: \n136: ---\n137: \n138: ## What FHIR Will Enable\n139: \n140: | Benefit | How |\n141: |---------|-----|\n142: | **Real-time sharing** | Automatic upload to clinical system |\n143: | **GP visibility** | Doctor sees data in EMIS/SystmOne |\n144: | **Hospital integration** | Consultant accesses during appointment |\n145: | **Research** | Anonymised data for NHS research |\n146: \n147: ---\n148: \n149: ## Timeline\n150: \n151: | Phase | When | What |\n152: |-------|------|------|\n153: | **Now** | Jul 2026 | Manual PDF/HTML reports |\n154: | **Phase 1** | Q4 2026 | NHS Innovation Service registration |\n155: | **Phase 2** | Q1 2027 | FHIR API access (when available) |\n156: | **Phase 3** | Q2 2027 | Full clinical system integration |\n157: \n158: ---\n159: \n160: ## Alternative: Nightscout → NHS\n161: \n162: Until FHIR is available:\n163: \n164: 1. **Export from Nightscout** → CSV/PDF\n165: 2. **Convert to AgentSON** → Structured data\n166: 3. **Generate report** → HTML/PDF\n167: 4. **Share with GP** → Email or in-person\n168: \n169: ---\n170: \n171: ## References\n172: \n173: - NHS FHIR Implementation Guide: https://fhir.nhs.uk\n174: - NHS 10-Year Plan: Digital health integration\n175: - Patient-initiated data sharing: Under development\n\n(End of file - total 175 lines)\n</content>",
      "status": "success",
      "timestamp": 1783296348875
