    },
    {
      "type": "action",
      "tool": "read",
      "code": "{\"filePath\": \"C:\\\\Users\\\\LLM-Test\\\\Documents\\\\agentsong\\\\docs\\\\standards\\\\adrs\\\\adr-010-gdpr-data-liberation.md\"}",
      "output": "<path>C:\\Users\\LLM-Test\\Documents\\agentsong\\docs\\standards\\adrs\\adr-010-gdpr-data-liberation.md</path>\n<type>file</type>\n<content>\n1: # ADR-010: AgentSON as GDPR/EU AI Act Data Liberation Tool\n2: \n3: **Status:** Accepted\n4: **Date:** 05 July 2026\n5: **Author:** Andrea Enning\n6: \n7: ---\n8: \n9: ## Context\n10: \n11: The parallels are exact:\n12: \n13: **Unsloth** made fine-tuning accessible to everyone. Before Unsloth, you needed a GPU cluster and a PhD. After Unsloth, you could fine-tune a 7B model on a single GPU in hours. Unsloth didn't create new capability — it democratized existing capability.\n14: \n15: **AgentSON** makes session data export accessible to everyone. Before AgentSON, your AI coding sessions were locked in proprietary databases with no export API. After AgentSON, you can export, search, replay, and fine-tune on your own data. AgentSON doesn't create new capability — it democratizes existing capability.\n16: \n17: The difference: Unsloth democratized model training. AgentSON democratizes data ownership.\n18: \n19: ## The Legal Right\n20: \n21: Users already have the legal right to their data. AgentSON makes it exercisable.\n22: \n23: ### GDPR Article 20 — Right to Data Portability\n24: \n25: > \"The data subject shall have the right to receive the personal data concerning him or her, which he or she has provided to a controller, in a structured, commonly used and machine-readable format.\"\n26: \n27: Every AI coding tool stores your prompts, code, and session data. Under GDPR, you have the right to receive that data in a machine-readable format. Most tools don't provide this. AgentSON does.\n28: \n29: ### EU AI Act — Transparency Requirements\n30: \n31: > \"Providers of AI systems shall ensure that the system is designed and developed in such a way that natural persons are informed that they are interacting with an AI system.\"\n32: \n33: > \"Users of AI systems that generate synthetic text... shall ensure that the outputs of the AI system are marked in a machine-readable format.\"\n34: \n35: The EU AI Act requires transparency about AI-generated content. AgentSON captures the full trace — what the AI did, what it generated, what tools it used — in a machine-readable format that satisfies transparency requirements.\n36: \n37: ### What This Means\n38: \n39: | Right | Legal basis | Tool status | AgentSON solution |\n40: |-------|-------------|-------------|-------------------|\n41: | Access your data | GDPR Art. 15 | Most tools: no export | AgentSON exports everything |\n42: | Export your data | GDPR Art. 20 | Most tools: no portable format | AgentSON is the portable format |\n43: | Transparency | EU AI Act Art. 52 | Most tools: opaque | AgentSON captures full trace |\n44: | Right to explanation | GDPR Art. 22 | Most tools: no audit trail | AgentSON has every thought + action |\n45: \n46: ## The Unsloth Analogy\n47: \n48: | Aspect | Unsloth | AgentSON |\n49: |--------|---------|----------|\n50: | What it democratized | Model fine-tuning | Session data export |\n51: | Before | GPU cluster + PhD needed | No export API, vendor lock-in |\n52: | After | Single GPU, hours | One CLI command, portable JSON |\n53: | Who benefits | Individual developers, small teams | Individual developers, small teams |\n54: | Legal basis | N/A | GDPR Art. 20, EU AI Act Art. 52 |\n55: | Business model | Open source, freemium | Open source, Apache 2.0 |\n56: \n57: ## Decision\n58: \n59: AgentSON is the Unsloth of session data. Not because it's technically similar — but because it serves the same role in the ecosystem:\n60: \n61: 1. **Democratizes access** — makes something previously only available to big players accessible to everyone\n62: 2. **Legal backing** — GDPR and EU AI Act give users the right; AgentSON makes it exercisable\n63: 3. **Open source** — Apache 2.0, no telemetry, no vendor lock-in\n64: 4. **Community-driven** — every new reader makes the format more valuable\n65: \n66: ## Consequences\n67: \n68: ### The Positioning\n69: \n70: AgentSON isn't competing with Cursor, Claude Code, or Copilot. It's the tool that lets users exercise their legal rights over the data those tools generate.\n71: \n72: - Cursor keeps your data captive → AgentSON exports it\n73: - Claude Code embeds spyware → AgentSON gives you ownership\n74: - Copilot stores traces in Microsoft servers → AgentSON makes them portable\n75: \n76: ### The Value Proposition\n77: \n78: > \"You have the legal right to your data. AgentSON is how you exercise it.\"\n79: \n80: This is stronger than \"open format for session traces\" because:\n81: - It's legally grounded (GDPR + EU AI Act)\n82: - It's emotionally resonant (data ownership, privacy, sovereignty)\n83: - It's practically useful (export, search, fine-tune)\n84: - It's defensible (legal right, not just nice-to-have)\n85: \n86: ### The Market\n87: \n88: Every developer using AI coding tools has this right. Most don't know how to exercise it. AgentSON teaches them.\n89: \n90: - 5M+ Cline users (BYOK = they care about data)\n91: - 6.5M opencode monthly devs (open source = they care about ownership)\n92: - 147K GitHub stars on opencode (community = advocacy)\n93: - Every Cursor user locked in (frustration = demand)\n94: \n95: ## The Thesis\n96: \n97: Unsloth democratized model training. AgentSON democratizes data ownership.\n98: \n99: Both serve the same constituency: individual developers and small teams who want the capabilities that were previously only available to big labs. Both are open source. Both are backed by legal rights (Unsloth by open research norms, AgentSON by GDPR and the EU AI Act).\n100: \n101: The $60B question isn't whether this data is valuable. It's who gets to use it.\n102: \n103: AgentSON's answer: you do. It's your legal right. Here's how to exercise it.\n\n(End of file - total 103 lines)\n</content>",
      "status": "success",
      "timestamp": 1783296351543
    },
    {
      "type": "action",
      "tool": "read",
      "code": "{\"filePath\": \"C:\\\\Users\\\\LLM-Test\\\\Documents\\\\AgentSON.wiki\\\\SOPs.md\"}",
      "output": "<path>C:\\Users\\LLM-Test\\Documents\\AgentSON.wiki\\SOPs.md</path>\n<type>file</type>\n<content>\n1: # Standard Operating Procedures (SOPs)\n2: \n3: 15 SOPs covering health data, AI sessions, infrastructure, and wiki deployment.\n4: \n5: ---\n6: \n7: ## SOP Index\n8: \n9: | # | Title | Category |\n10: |---|-------|----------|\n11: | 001 | [Reading FreeStyle Libre 2 Sensor](SOP-001) | Health |\n12: | 002 | [Converting Libre Data to AgentSON](SOP-002) | Health |\n13: | 003 | [Viewing Glucose Data in Browser](SOP-003) | Health |\n14: | 004 | [Exporting AI Sessions](SOP-004) | AI Sessions |\n15: | 005 | [Searching AI Sessions](SOP-005) | AI Sessions |\n16: | 006 | [Sharing Data with Doctors](SOP-006) | Health |\n17: | 007 | [Setting Up Nightscout Server](SOP-007) | Infrastructure |\n18: | 008 | [WhatsApp Bot Setup](SOP-008) | Infrastructure |\n19: | 009 | [TV Dashboard Setup](SOP-009) | Infrastructure |\n20: | 010 | [Setting Up MedGemma HAI-DEF](SOP-010) | Health/AI |\n21: | 011 | [Fine-tuning MedGemma on Glucose Data](SOP-011) | Health/AI |\n22: | 012 | [Setting Up Juggluco on Mother's Phone](SOP-012) | Health |\n23: | 013 | [NHS FHIR Integration](SOP-013) | Health |\n24: | 014 | [West Africa Voice Alerts](SOP-014) | Health/Localization |\n25: | 015 | [Creating GitHub Wiki (Manual + Programmatic)](SOP-015) | Infrastructure |\n26: \n27: ---\n28: \n29: ## Health SOPs\n30: \n31: ### SOP-001: Reading FreeStyle Libre 2 Sensor\n32: \n33: Read glucose data from FreeStyle Libre 2 continuous glucose monitor using NFC.\n34: \n35: **Prerequisites:**\n36: - FreeStyle Libre 2 sensor\n37: - Android phone with NFC\n38: - LibreLink app installed\n39: \n40: **Steps:**\n41: 1. Open LibreLink app\n42: 2. Scan sensor with NFC\n43: 3. Export CSV from app\n44: 4. Run `agentson import --tool libre --input libre_data.csv`\n45: \n46: ---\n47: \n48: ### SOP-002: Converting Libre Data to AgentSON\n49: \n50: Convert FreeStyle Libre 2 CSV export to AgentSON format.\n51: \n52: ```bash\n53: # Import Libre CSV\n54: agentson import --tool libre --input libre_data.csv --output session.AgentSON\n55: ```\n56: \n57: ---\n58: \n59: ### SOP-003: Viewing Glucose Data in Browser\n60: \n61: View glucose data in the web viewer with trend charts.\n62: \n63: 1. Open `docs/viewer/index.html`\n64: 2. Drag and drop `.AgentSON` file\n65: 3. View trend chart and statistics\n66: \n67: ---\n68: \n69: ## AI Session SOPs\n70: \n71: ### SOP-004: Exporting AI Sessions\n72: \n73: Export sessions from any supported tool.\n74: \n75: ```bash\n76: # Export from opencode\n77: agentson export --tool opencode --session ses_xxx --output ./sessions/\n78: \n79: # Export from Claude Code\n80: agentson export --tool claude-code --session session_xxx --output ./sessions/\n81: ```\n82: \n83: ---\n84: \n85: ### SOP-005: Searching AI Sessions\n86: \n87: Full-text search across all exported sessions.\n88: \n89: ```bash\n90: # Search for a keyword\n91: agentson search \"nightscout\" --tool opencode\n92: \n93: # Search across all tools\n94: agentson search \"auth bug\"\n95: ```\n96: \n97: ---\n98: \n99: ## Infrastructure SOPs\n100: \n101: ### SOP-007: Setting Up Nightscout Server\n102: \n103: Self-host Nightscout for glucose data cloud sync.\n104: \n105: **Prerequisites:**\n106: - Oracle Cloud Always Free tier (or any VPS)\n107: - Docker installed\n108: \n109: **Steps:**\n110: 1. Deploy Nightscout Docker container\n111: 2. Configure MongoDB\n112: 3. Set API secret\n113: 4. Connect LibreLink app\n114: \n115: ---\n116: \n117: ### SOP-013: NHS FHIR Integration\n118: \n119: Share glucose data with NHS doctors via FHIR API.\n120: \n121: **Status:** Planned — requires NHS Digital FHIR credentials\n122: \n123: ---\n124: \n125: ## Health/AI SOPs\n126: \n127: ### SOP-010: Setting Up MedGemma HAI-DEF\n128: \n129: Set up Google's MedGemma model for glucose data analysis.\n130: \n131: ### SOP-011: Fine-tuning MedGemma on Glucose Data\n132: \n133: Fine-tune MedGemma on personal glucose data for personalized insights.\n134: \n135: ---\n136: \n137: ## Infrastructure SOPs (Wiki)\n138: \n139: ### SOP-015: Creating GitHub Wiki (Manual + Programmatic)\n140: \n141: Create and populate a GitHub wiki — manually via browser or programmatically via clone-and-push.\n142: \n143: **Prerequisites:**\n144: - GitHub account\n145: - Git installed\n146: - Classic PAT with `repo` scope\n147: \n148: **Method 1: Manual (Browser)**\n149: 1. Go to `github.com/USER/REPO/wiki`\n150: 2. Click \"Create the first page\"\n151: 3. Edit, save, repeat\n152: \n153: **Method 2: Clone and Push (Recommended)**\n154: ```bash\n155: git clone https://github.com/USER/REPO.wiki.git\n156: # Copy markdown files into cloned repo\n157: git add . && git commit -m \"Add wiki pages\"\n158: # Push with PAT embedded in URL\n159: ```\n160: \n161: **Method 3: Programmatic with OpenCode**\n162: 1. Prompt OpenCode to generate markdown pages\n163: 2. Review locally\n164: 3. Push manually (Method 2)\n165: \n166: **Common errors:**\n167: - \"Password authentication not supported\" → Embed PAT in URL\n168: - \"Invalid username or token\" → Use classic PAT, not fine-grained\n169: - \"Repository not found\" → Wiki URL needs `.wiki.git` suffix\n\n(End of file - total 169 lines)\n</content>",
