    },
    {
      "type": "action",
      "tool": "read",
      "code": "{\"filePath\": \"C:\\\\Users\\\\LLM-Test\\\\Documents\\\\AgentSON.wiki\\\\Mental-Models.md\"}",
      "output": "<path>C:\\Users\\LLM-Test\\Documents\\AgentSON.wiki\\Mental-Models.md</path>\n<type>file</type>\n<content>\n1: # Mental Models\n2: \n3: How we think about problems before writing code.\n4: \n5: ---\n6: \n7: ## Simplicity First\n8: \n9: **The simplest solution that works is the best solution.**\n10: \n11: If you can solve a problem with a 20-line Python script, don't build a microservice. If a JSON file does the job, don't reach for a database. Complexity is a cost, not a feature.\n12: \n13: **In practice:**\n14: - AgentSON is a JSON file, not a database\n15: - The viewer is a single HTML file, no build step\n16: - The CLI is a flat Python module, no framework\n17: \n18: **The test:** Can you explain the solution to someone in 2 sentences? If not, it's too complex.\n19: \n20: ---\n21: \n22: ## Own Your Data\n23: \n24: **Never depend on a vendor for something you can store yourself.**\n25: \n26: If your glucose data lives in Dexcom's cloud, you don't own it. If your session history lives in OpenAI's servers, you don't own it. If the company shuts down, your data disappears.\n27: \n28: **In practice:**\n29: - .AgentSON files live on your machine\n30: - Nightscout is self-hosted\n31: - No account required for anything\n32: \n33: **The test:** If the internet goes down for a week, can you still access everything you need?\n34: \n35: ---\n36: \n37: ## Build to Learn\n38: \n39: **Build things to understand them, not just to use them.**\n40: \n41: The Chrome DevTools reader exists because I wanted to understand how Chrome stores AI assistance history. The glucose reader exists because I wanted to understand how FreeStyle Libre data is structured. Building teaches better than reading documentation.\n42: \n43: **In practice:**\n44: - Write the parser yourself before using a library\n45: - Read the SQLite schema yourself before using an ORM\n46: - Understand the format before building the tool\n47: \n48: **The test:** Can you explain how it works under the hood, not just how to use it?\n49: \n50: ---\n51: \n52: ## Constraint-Driven\n53: \n54: **Limitations are features, not bugs.**\n55: \n56: A GTX 1050 with 2GB VRAM means no 7B models locally. That constraint drove fine-tuning smaller models, which led to better results on specific tasks than a general 7B model would give.\n57: \n58: **In practice:**\n59: - £0 build budget → everything must be free or self-hosted\n60: - 2GB VRAM → quantized models, distillation, API fallback\n61: - Limited time → single-file solutions, no build pipelines\n62: \n63: **The test:** Would this solution still work on a 5-year-old laptop with no internet?\n64: \n65: ---\n66: \n67: ## One File, One Truth\n68: \n69: **A single file should contain everything needed.**\n70: \n71: A .AgentSON file has the schema, the entries, the metadata, the context. You don't need a database, a config file, and a log. One file. One truth.\n72: \n73: **In practice:**\n74: - One .AgentSON = one complete session\n75: - One SOP = one complete procedure\n76: - One HTML file = one complete viewer\n77: \n78: **The test:** Can you send someone one file and have everything they need?\n79: \n80: ---\n81: \n82: ## Say What's Tested\n83: \n84: **Never imply unearned confidence.**\n85: \n86: If something is written but untested, say \"written, untested.\" If it's tested against real data, say \"tested against real data.\" If it's tested against synthetic fixtures, say \"tested against synthetic fixtures.\"\n87: \n88: **In practice:**\n89: - README badges reflect actual test results\n90: - Status labels match reality\n91: - No aspirational claims\n92: \n93: **The test:** Would a skeptic agree with your status label?\n\n(End of file - total 93 lines)\n</content>",
      "status": "success",
      "timestamp": 1783296356052
    },
    {
      "type": "action",
      "tool": "read",
      "code": "{\"filePath\": \"C:\\\\Users\\\\LLM-Test\\\\Documents\\\\agentsong\\\\docs\\\\standards\\\\adrs\\\\adr-012-intrinsic-before-extrinsic.md\"}",
      "output": "<path>C:\\Users\\LLM-Test\\Documents\\agentsong\\docs\\standards\\adrs\\adr-012-intrinsic-before-extrinsic.md</path>\n<type>file</type>\n<content>\n1: # ADR-012: Intrinsic Before Extrinsic\n2: \n3: **Status:** Proposed\n4: **Date:** 05 July 2026\n5: **Author:** Andrea Enning\n6: \n7: ---\n8: \n9: ## Context\n10: \n11: As AgentSON grows, there is a risk of accumulating application-specific concerns into the core specification. Features like fine-tuning export, analytics, compliance, and dashboards are valuable — but they are **uses** of the artifact, not **properties** of it.\n12: \n13: Without a clear boundary, the specification could become a kitchen sink that tries to serve every use case, diluting its focus and making it harder to implement.\n14: \n15: ## Decision\n16: \n17: AgentSON Core SHALL evolve only to improve the **intrinsic properties** of an execution episode:\n18: \n19: 1. **Fidelity** — does it accurately represent what happened?\n20: 2. **Portability** — can it move between systems?\n21: 3. **Replayability** — can the execution be reconstructed?\n22: 4. **Analyzability** — can humans and software inspect it?\n23: \n24: Applications that consume AgentSON (training, archives, dashboards, analytics, compliance, benchmarking, etc.) are intentionally **outside** the core specification. Their ability to exist is a consequence of the specification, not its purpose.\n25: \n26: ## The Architecture\n27: \n28: ```\n29:                     AgentSON Core\n30: \n31:          Fidelity\n32:              │\n33:          Portability\n34:              │\n35:         Replayability\n36:              │\n37:         Analyzability\n38:              │\n39:              ▼\n40: \n41:         Stable Execution Record\n42: \n43:              ▼\n44: \n45:         Everything Else\n46: \n47:     • Fine-tuning\n48:     • Compliance\n49:     • Search\n50:     • Replay UI\n51:     • Archives\n52:     • Benchmarks\n53:     • Analytics\n54: ```\n55: \n56: Every downstream application depends on the core. The core depends on none of them.\n57: \n58: ## Test for New Features\n59: \n60: When proposing a new feature, ask:\n61: \n62: > \"Does this change improve one of the four intrinsic properties?\"\n63: \n64: - **If yes** → candidate for the core\n65: - **If no** → belongs in a downstream package, plugin, or application\n66: \n67: ## Analogies\n68: \n69: | Standard | What it doesn't know about |\n70: |----------|--------------------------|\n71: | Git | Pull requests |\n72: | PDF | E-signatures |\n73: | OpenTelemetry | Dashboards |\n74: | PCAP | Intrusion detection |\n75: | **AgentSON** | Fine-tuning, analytics, compliance |\n76: \n77: ## Consequences\n78: \n79: ### Positive\n80: - Clean separation of concerns\n81: - Specification stays focused and minimal\n82: - Downstream tools can innovate freely\n83: - Easy to evaluate new feature proposals\n84: \n85: ### Negative\n86: - Some features that could be in the spec will live in packages\n87: - Users need to assemble their own toolchain\n88: \n89: ### Neutral\n90: - The boundary is explicit and documented\n91: - Can be revisited if the ecosystem demands convergence\n\n(End of file - total 91 lines)\n</content>",
