      "output": "Found 38 matches\nC:\\Users\\LLM-Test\\Documents\\agentsong\\issues\\issue-healthcare-data-interoperability.md:\n  Line 7: ## Legal context (what GDPR actually says)\n\n  Line 9: ### GDPR Article 20 — Right to data portability\n\n  Line 14: ### What GDPR requires vs. doesn't require\n\n  Line 30: ### GDPR compliance baseline\n\n  Line 32: CSV export usually already satisfies compliance baseline. Even if it is annoying, manual, or behind a login.\n\n  Line 85: The absence of APIs is not automatically a compliance failure — it's a design trade-off under regulated constraints.\n\n  Line 103: Law says \"you own your data.\" Systems still behave like \"data is leased via interface.\" That tension is why formats like AgentSON matter — not as GDPR enforcement, but as interoperability representations of system behaviour over time.\n\n  Line 107: 1. GDPR Article 20: https://eur-lex.europa.eu/legal-content/EN/TXT/?uri=CELEX%3A32016R0679\n\n\nC:\\Users\\LLM-Test\\Documents\\agentsong\\issues\\issue-competitive-landscape-agentlog.md:\n  Line 33: | Constraints | compliance, SOC2, audit | usability, flexibility |\n\n\nC:\\Users\\LLM-Test\\Documents\\agentsong\\wiki\\SOP-015-Creating-GitHub-Wiki.md:\n  Line 243: - [GDPR Article 20 — Right to Data Portability](https://gdpr-info.eu/art-20-gdpr/)\n\n\nC:\\Users\\LLM-Test\\Documents\\agentsong\\docs\\standards\\adrs\\adr-012-intrinsic-before-extrinsic.md:\n  Line 11: As AgentSON grows, there is a risk of accumulating application-specific concerns into the core specification. Features like fine-tuning export, analytics, compliance, and dashboards are valuable — but they are **uses** of the artifact, not **properties** of it.\n\n  Line 24: Applications that consume AgentSON (training, archives, dashboards, analytics, compliance, benchmarking, etc.) are intentionally **outside** the core specification. Their ability to exist is a consequence of the specification, not its purpose.\n\n  Line 75: | **AgentSON** | Fine-tuning, analytics, compliance |\n\n\nC:\\Users\\LLM-Test\\Documents\\agentsong\\issues\\issue-design-principle-intrinsic-before-extrinsic.md:\n  Line 12: Everything else (fine-tuning, analytics, compliance, dashboards, archives, search, benchmarking) is an **extrinsic use** of the artifact, not a property of it.\n\n  Line 29: compliance, benchmarking, etc.) are intentionally outside the core specification.\n\n  Line 50: | **AgentSON** | Fine-tuning, analytics, compliance |\n\n  Line 60: - ADR-010: GDPR/EU AI Act Data Liberation\n\n\nC:\\Users\\LLM-Test\\Documents\\agentsong\\wiki\\ADRs.md:\n  Line 20: | 010 | [GDPR Data Liberation](ADR-010) | 2026-07-05 | Accepted |\n\n  Line 77: ## ADR-010: GDPR Data Liberation\n\n  Line 79: **Context:** GDPR Article 20 gives users the right to export data in machine-readable format. Most AI tools don't provide this.\n\n  Line 81: **Decision:** Position AgentSON as the tool to exercise GDPR data rights for AI session data. Add \"Unsloth analogy\" — democratizing data ownership like Unsloth democratized fine-tuning.\n\n  Line 85: - (+) EU AI Act compliance built-in\n\n\nC:\\Users\\LLM-Test\\Documents\\agentsong\\wiki\\Home.md:\n  Line 23: **GDPR Article 20** gives you the right to export your data in a machine-readable format. **The EU AI Act** requires transparency about AI-generated content. Most tools don't provide this. AgentSON does.\n\n\nC:\\Users\\LLM-Test\\Documents\\agentsong\\README.md:\n  Line 28: **GDPR Article 20** gives you the right to export your data in a machine-readable format. **The EU AI Act** requires transparency about AI-generated content. Most tools don't provide this. AgentSON does.\r\n\n  Line 193: 6. **Legal compliance** — GDPR Art. 20 + EU AI Act Art. 52\r\n\n\nC:\\Users\\LLM-Test\\Documents\\agentsong\\docs\\standards\\adrs\\adr-010-gdpr-data-liberation.md:\n  Line 1: # ADR-010: AgentSON as GDPR/EU AI Act Data Liberation Tool\r\n\n  Line 23: ### GDPR Article 20 — Right to Data Portability\r\n\n  Line 27: Every AI coding tool stores your prompts, code, and session data. Under GDPR, you have the right to receive that data in a machine-readable format. Most tools don't provide this. AgentSON does.\r\n\n  Line 41: | Access your data | GDPR Art. 15 | Most tools: no export | AgentSON exports everything |\r\n\n  Line 42: | Export your data | GDPR Art. 20 | Most tools: no portable format | AgentSON is the portable format |\r\n\n  Line 44: | Right to explanation | GDPR Art. 22 | Most tools: no audit trail | AgentSON has every thought + action |\r\n\n  Line 54: | Legal basis | N/A | GDPR Art. 20, EU AI Act Art. 52 |\r\n\n  Line 62: 2. **Legal backing** — GDPR and EU AI Act give users the right; AgentSON makes it exercisable\r\n\n  Line 81: - It's legally grounded (GDPR + EU AI Act)\r\n\n  Line 99: Both serve the same constituency: individual developers and small teams who want the capabilities that were previously only available to big labs. Both are open source. Both are backed by legal rights (Unsloth by open research norms, AgentSON by GDPR and the EU AI Act).\r\n\n\nC:\\Users\\LLM-Test\\Documents\\agentsong\\docs\\standards\\README.md:\n  Line 69: | [ADR-010](adrs/adr-010-gdpr-data-liberation.md) | AgentSON as GDPR/EU AI Act data liberation tool (the Unsloth analogy) |\r\n\n\nC:\\Users\\LLM-Test\\Documents\\agentsong\\docs\\sops\\SOP-011-Fine-tuning-MedGemma-on-Glucose-Data.md:\n  Line 118: | **HIPAA compliant** | Keep data local, don't upload to cloud |\n\n\nC:\\Users\\LLM-Test\\Documents\\agentsong\\SOPs\\SOP-011-Fine-tuning-MedGemma-on-Glucose-Data.md:\n  Line 118: | **HIPAA compliant** | Keep data local, don't upload to cloud |\n",
