      "output": "<path>C:\\Users\\LLM-Test\\Documents\\agentsong\\docs\\standards\\adrs\\adr-001-agentSON-format.md</path>\n<type>file</type>\n<content>\n1: # ADR-001: Why AgentSON Exists as a Format\n2: \n3: **Status:** Accepted\n4: **Date:** 04 July 2026\n5: **Author:** Andrea Enning\n6: \n7: ---\n8: \n9: ## Context\n10: \n11: Every AI coding agent stores session data in its own proprietary SQLite database. OpenAI has one schema, MiniMax has another, Chrome DevTools has a completely different structure. There is no standard format for exporting, sharing, or analyzing AI agent sessions.\n12: \n13: When I switched from one tool to another, I lost all my context. When I wanted to compare how different agents handled the same problem, I couldn't. When I wanted to fine-tune a model on my own sessions, I had to write a different parser for every tool.\n14: \n15: ## Decision\n16: \n17: Create a single, vendor-neutral JSON format (.AgentSON) that captures the full structure of an AI agent session: who said what, what was thought, what actions were taken, what results were observed.\n18: \n19: ## Consequences\n20: \n21: ### Positive\n22: - Sessions are portable between tools\n23: - One parser works for all sessions\n24: - Fine-tuning pipelines can target a single format\n25: - Sessions can be searched, sorted, and analyzed uniformly\n26: \n27: ### Negative\n28: - Every tool needs a reader/converter\n29: - The format must accommodate the lowest common denominator\n30: - Some tool-specific features may not map cleanly\n31: \n32: ### Neutral\n33: - The format will evolve (v1.0 → v1.1 → ...) as new tools emerge\n34: - Backward compatibility is mandatory — old files must always work\n\n(End of file - total 34 lines)\n</content>",
